50|$|In the United States, {{attestation}} clauses {{were introduced}} into probate law with the promulgation {{of the first}} version of the Model Probate Code in the 1940s. Statutes that authorize self-proved wills typically provide that a will that contains this language will be admitted to probate without affidavits from the <b>attesting</b> <b>witnesses.</b>|$|R
50|$|As a lawyer, a civil-law notary draws up and executes legal {{instruments}} called notarial instruments (Fr acte notarié, Sp instrumento notarial, It atto notarile, Du notariële akte, Ger notarielle Urkunde, Notariatsurkunde). To be valid, a notarial instrument must be signed contemporaneously (uno contextu) by the appearer(s) (parties to the instrument), {{sometimes in the}} presence of <b>attesting</b> <b>witnesses,</b> before the notary who also signs and officiates the signing ceremony.|$|R
